    <definition xml:id="def-vertical-line-test">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>vertical line test</term> is a method used to determine whether a relation on a graph is a function. </p>
          <p>Start by drawing a vertical line anywhere on the graph and observe the number of times the relation on the graph intersects with the vertical line. If the vertical line intersects the graph at exactly one point, then the relation is a function. If, however, the graph of the relation intersects the vertical line more than once (anywhere on the graph), then the relations is not a function.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity xml:id="FN1-determine-if-function-using-vertical-line-test">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Determine whether each of the following graphs are functions by using the vertical line test (<xref ref="def-vertical-line-test"/>).
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <image>
      <sageplot>
        f(x)=sqrt(9-x^2)
        g(x)=-(sqrt(9-x^2))
        p=plot(f, (x, -3, 3), ymin=-4, ymax=4, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)+ plot(g, (x, -3, 3), ymin=-4, ymax=4, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
        p
      </sageplot>
    </image>
  </task>
  <task>
    <image>
      <sageplot>
        f(x) = -4*x^3+2*x^2+3
        p=plot(f, (x, -5, 5), ymin=-15, ymax=15, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
        p
      </sageplot>
    </image>
  </task>
  <task>
    <image>
      <sageplot>
        f(x)=5*x-1
        p=plot(f, (x, -5, 5), ymin=-10, ymax=10, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
        p
      </sageplot>
    </image>
  </task>
  <task>
    <image>
      <sageplot>
        f(x)=sqrt(x)
        g(x)=-(sqrt(x))
        p=plot(f, (x, 0, 5), ymin=-10, ymax=10, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)+ plot(g, (x, 0, 5), ymin=-10, ymax=10, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
        p
      </sageplot>
    </image>
  </task>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="FN1-determine-if-function-from-equation">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let's explore how to look at an equation to determine if it is a function.
    </p>
  </introduction>
<task>
    <p>
      Suppose you are given the equation <m>x^2+y^2=9</m>.
      <ul>
        <li>
            If <m>x=4</m>, what kind of <m>y</m>-values would you get for <m>x^2+y^2=9</m>?
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Based on this information, do you think <m>x^2+y^2=9</m> is a function? 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
</task>
<task>
  <p>
    Suppose you are given the equation <m>y=3x^2+2</m>.
    <ul>
      <li>
          If <m>x=4</m>, what kind of <m>y</m>-values would you get for <m>y=3x^2+2</m>?
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Based on this information, do you think <m>y=3x^2+2</m> is a function? 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</task><task>
  <p>
    Suppose you are given the equation <m>x=y^2</m>.
    <ul>
      <li>
          If <m>x=4</m>, what kind of <m>y</m>-values would you get for <m>x=y^2</m>?
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Based on this information, do you think <m>x=y^2</m> is a function? 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</task><task>
  <p>
    Suppose you are given the equation <m>y=-4x-3</m>.
    <ul>
      <li>
          If <m>x=4</m>, what kind of <m>y</m>-values would you get for <m>y=-4x-3</m>?
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Based on this information, do you think <m>y=-4x-3</m> is a function? 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</task>
<task>
    <p>
      How can you look at an equation to determine whether or not it is a function?
    </p>
</task>
</activity>

<remark>
  Notice that <xref ref="FN1-determine-if-function-from-equation"/> shows that equations with a <m>y^2</m> term generally do not define functions.
</remark>

<activity xml:id="FN1-determine-domain-from-equation-square-root">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      It's important to be able to determine the domain of any equation, especially when thinking about functions. Answer the following questions given the equation <m>y=\sqrt{x}</m>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <p>
      What values of <m>x</m> would give an error (if any)?
      <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
        <li> <m>-2</m> </li>
        <li> <m> 0</m> </li>
        <li> <m>4</m> </li>
        <li> <m>-5</m> </li></ol></p>
  </task>
  <task>
      <p>
        Based on this information, what values of <m>x</m> would the equation exist? 
        <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
          <li> <m>-2</m> </li>
          <li> <m> 0</m> </li>
          <li> <m>4</m> </li>
          <li> <m>-5</m> </li></ol>
      </p>
  </task>
  <task>
      <p>
        How can we represent the domain of this equation in interval notation?
        <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
          <li> <m>(-\infty,0)</m> </li>
          <li> <m> (0,\infty)</m> </li>
          <li> <m>(0, 0)</m> </li>
          <li> <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m> </li></ol>
      </p>
  </task>
</activity>
  
  <activity xml:id="FN1-determine-domain-from-equation-linear">
    <introduction>
      <p>
       Answer the following questions given the equation <m>y=-5x+1</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <p>
        What values of <m>x</m> would give an error (if any)?
        <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
          <li> <m>-2</m> </li>
          <li> <m> 0</m> </li>
          <li> <m>4</m> </li>
          <li> <m>-5</m> </li></ol></p>
    </task>
    <task>
        <p>
          Based on this information, what values of <m>x</m> would the equation exist? 
          <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
            <li> <m>-2</m> </li>
            <li> <m> 0</m> </li>
            <li> <m>4</m> </li>
            <li> <m>-5</m> </li></ol>
        </p>
    </task>
    <task>
        <p>
          How can we represent the domain of this equation in interval notation?
          <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
            <li> <m>(-\infty,0)</m> </li>
            <li> <m> (0,\infty)</m> </li>
            <li> <m>(-5, 1)</m> </li>
            <li> <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m> </li></ol>
        </p>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <activity xml:id="FN1-determine-domain-from-equation-rational">
    <introduction>
      <p>
       Answer the following questions given the equation <m>y=\frac{3}{x-5}</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <p>
        What values of <m>x</m> would give an error (if any)?
        <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
          <li> <m>-3</m> </li>
          <li> <m> 0</m> </li>
          <li> <m>-4</m> </li>
          <li> <m>5</m> </li></ol></p>
    </task>
    <task>
        <p>
          Based on this information, what values of <m>x</m> would the equation exist? 
          <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
            <li> <m>-3</m> </li>
            <li> <m> 0</m> </li>
            <li> <m>-4</m> </li>
            <li> <m>5</m> </li></ol>
        </p>
    </task>
    <task>
        <p>
          How can we represent the domain of this equation in interval notation?
          <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
            <li> <m>(-\infty,5)</m> </li>
            <li> <m> (5,\infty)</m> </li>
            <li> <m>(-5, 5)</m> </li>
            <li> <m>(-\infty,5)</m>U<m>(5,\infty)</m> </li></ol>
        </p>
    </task>
</activity>

<remark>
  When determining the domain of an equation, it is often easier to first find values of <m>x</m> that make the function undefined. Once you have those values, then you know that <m>x</m> can be any value but those.
</remark>
